\section{Skew Confluence} \label{sec:skew-confluence}

We now consider a modified grammar for \versecalc{} in which there is an additional kind of value, a \emph{fixpoint} value:
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{lr@@{\;}c@@{\;}l}
      \text{Values} & |v| & ::= & |x|  \vb \hnf \vb |mu x hnf| \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
and a modified set of unification rewrite rules $\mathcal{U}$ in which rule \rulename{u-occurs} is modified from
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulename{u-occurs} & |x=V^[x]| & \movesto & |fail| & \text{if $|V| \ne |hole|$} \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
to
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulename{u-occurs} & |x=hnf| & \movesto & |x=mu x hnf| & \text{if $|x| \in \freevars{|hnf|}$} \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
and to which a new rewrite rule is added:
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulename{u-unwrap} & |mu x hnf| & \movesto & |subst hnf x (mu x hnf)| \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
As we will see, rule \rulename{u-unwrap} is confluent but not Noetherian.

The resulting grammar is not confluent. \guy{explain even-odd-problem}
Therefore we will modify the proof of confluence for $\runi$ to become a proof of \emph{skew confluence} \cite{Ariola2002},
and then go on to prove that \versecalc{} itself, with this modification, is skew confluent.


\subsection{Substitution}

We use the notation |subst e x v| to denote the expression that results from performing standard capture-avoiding substitution of the value |v| for every occurrence of the variable |x| within the expression |e| (it turns out that, for \versecalc{}, substitution of general expressions for variables is not required, only substitution of values for variables).
Figure~\ref{fig:substitution} contains a formal definition of how this notation applies to the \versecalc{} grammar (compare \cite[\S 2.1.15]{Barendregt}).

\begin{figure}
$
\begin{array}{r@@{\;\;}c@@{\;\;}l@@{\qquad}l}
  |subst x x v| & \equiv & |v| \\
  |subst y x v| & \equiv & |y| & \text{if $y \neq x$}  \\
  |subst k x v| & \equiv & |k| \\
  |subst op x v| & \equiv & |op| \\
  |substNP (arr (v_1, dots, v_n)) x v| & \equiv & |arr (subst v_1 x v, dots, subst v_n x v)| \\
  |subst (lam y e) x v| & \equiv & |lam y (subst e x v)| &  \text{if $y \not\in \freevars{|x|, |v|}$ [use $\alpha$]} \\
  |subst (mu y v') x v| & \equiv & |mu y (subst v' x v)| &  \text{if $y \not\in \freevars{|x|, |v|}$ [use $\alpha$]} \\
  |subst (eu; e) x v| & \equiv &  |subst eu x v; subst e x v| \\
  |subst (v' = e) x v| & \equiv &  |subst v' x v = subst e x v| \\
  |subst (def y e) x v| & \equiv & |def y (subst e x v)| &  \text{if $y \not\in \freevars{|x|, |v|}$ [use $\alpha$]} \\
  |subst fail x v| & \equiv & |fail| \\
  |subst (e_1 choice e_2) x v| & \equiv &  |subst e_1 x v`choice`subst e_2 x v| \\
  |subst (apply1N v_1 v_2) x v| & \equiv &  |applyNP (subst v_1 x v) (subst v_2 x v)| \\
  |subst (one e) x v| & \equiv & |one (subst e x v)| \\
  |subst (all e) x v| & \equiv & |all (subst e x v)| \\
\end{array}
$
\caption{Definition of the substitution notation |subst e x v|}\label{fig:substitution}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Unwrapping of Fixpoints is Confluent but not Noetherian}

\begin{lemma}\label{lem:unwrap-confluent}
The rule \rulename{u-unwrap} is confluent.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  Suppose that $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_1|}$ and $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_2|}$ for distinct redexes within $e$.
  
  If the redexes are disjoint, then \cref{lem:disjoint} applies.

  Otherwise, without loss of generality assume the redex for $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_1|}$ contains the redex for $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_2|}$;
  let $e$ must be of the form |C_1^[mu x (C_2^[mu y hnf])]| ($\alpha$-conversion may be used to ensure that $x$ and $y$ are distinct variables).

  Then |e_1 = C_1^[substNP (C_2^[mu y hnf]) x (mu x (C_2^[mu y hnf]))]|
  and |e_2 = C_1^[mu x (C_2^[subst hnf y (mu y hnf)])]|.

  From |e_2| we can take just one more \rulename{u-unwrap} step, using the outermost redex |mu x (C_2^[cdots])|, obtaining |e' = C_1^[subst (C_2^[subst hnf y (mu y hnf)]) x (mu x (C_2^[subst hnf y (mu y hnf)]))]|.

  \guy{More to come.}

  Thus we have $\rsteps{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e_1|}{|e'|}$ and $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e_2|}{|e'|}$, so \rulename{u-unwrap} is strongly confluent,
  and therefore by \cref{lem:strong} is confluent.
\end{proof}

To see that \rulename{u-unwrap} is not Noetherian, observe that
$$\ensuremath{|mu x (tup (1,x))| \go{\rulename{u-unwrap}}  |tup (1, mu x (tup (1,x)))| \go{\rulename{u-unwrap}} |tup (1, (tup (1, mu x (tup (1,x)))))| \go{\rulename{u-unwrap}} \cdots}$$
is an unending sequence of reduction steps.

\subsection{Information Content}

We define a second grammar, for a second language $\vcOmega$, by adding one more value |Omega|, which indicates a lack of information as to just what will be computed.
When |Omega| appears in a context where only a value is permitted, it indicates uncertainty as to what value will be provided; 
when |Omega| appears in a context where any expression permitted, it furthermore indicates uncertainty as to how many values will be provided (possibly none).
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{lr@@{\;}c@@{\;}l}
      \text{Values} & |v| & ::= & |x| \vb \hnf \vb |mu x hnf| \vb |Omega| \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}

For every term of \versecalc{} there is a corresponding term of $\vcOmega$, identical in structure and appearance and containing no occurrence of |Omega|;
we identify such terms and regard the set of terms of \versecalc{} as simply a subset of the terms of $\vcOmega$.

The definition of substitution (FIgure~\ref{fig:substitution}) is extended in the expected trivial manner: $|subst Omega x v| \equiv |Omega|$.

\begin{definition}
(after \cite[Definition 2.3]{Ariola2002})
Let |T| be a set of terms over a signature that includes the constant |Omega|.
Define $\leqomega^T$ be the relation such that $|Omega| \leqomega^T |M|$ for every term $|M| \in |T|$;
then define $\leqomega$ to be the transitive, reflexive, and compatible closure of $\leqomega^T$.
\end{definition}

Figure~\ref{fig:info-rewrite-rules} shows a system $\rinfo$ of rewrite rules on $\vcOmega$.
These may be compared to similar rules for the $\lambda\circ$ calculus \cite[Definition 5.20]{Ariola2002}.

\begin{figure}
 $
  \begin{array}{l}
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulegroupname{Information Content:~$\rinfo${}}
  \rulename{info-fix} & |mu x v| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-seq} & |eu; e| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-exi} & |def x e| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-fail} & |fail| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-choice-omega} & |Omega choice e| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-choice-assoc} & |(e_1 choice e_2) choice e_3| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-app-omega} & |apply1N Omega v| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-app-hnf} & |apply1N hnf v| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-one} & |one e| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-all} & |all e| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
\end{array}
\end{array}
$
\caption{Rewrite rules on $\vcOmega$ for defining the function $\omegavc(e)$}\label{fig:info-rewrite-rules}
\end{figure}

\begin{lemma}[$\rinfo$-Confluent] \label{lem:rinfo-c}
$\rinfo$ is locally confluent and noetherian; therefore $\rinfo$ is confluent.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
There is only one critical pair, arising from rules \rulename{info-choice} and \rulename{info-assoc}; that pair is |Omega choice e| and |Omega|.
That pair joins at |Omega| in one step, using rule \rulename{info-choice}. Therefore $\rinfo$ is locally confluent.

Let the size of a term of $\vcOmega$ be the number of tokens it contains other than |Omega| and parentheses.
Each of the rewrite rules in Figure~\ref{fig:info-rewrite-rules} strictly decreases the number of such tokens.
Because any given term has a finite number $n$ of such tokens, and the number of tokens cannot be less than zero,
for every term every rewriting sequence from that term can have no more than $n$ steps. So $\rinfo$ is bounded and therefore noetherian.

Because $\rinfo$ is locally confluent and noetherian, it is confluent by Newman's lemma.
\end{proof}

Because $\rinfo$ is confluent and noetherian, it follows that $\rinfo$ defines unique normal forms for $\vcOmega$. Therefore we are justified in defining
$\omegavc(e)$ to be the function that takes any term in $\vcOmega$ and returns the term that is its normal form.

\begin{definition}
The comparison $e \leqomegavc e'$ is defined to mean $\omegavc(e) \leqomega \omegavc(e')$.
\end{definition}
\guy{Need to prove that $\leqomegavc$ is monotonic with respect to $\leqomega$; this should be routine as per Skew paper \cite[Proposition 5.21]{Ariola2002}.}

\begin{lemma}[\versecalc{} monotonic] \label{lem:vc-monotonic}
Every rewrite rule in \versecalc{} is monotonic with respect to $\leqomegavc$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  Proof sketch. The left-hand side of every rule in $\rapp \cup \runi \cup \rcon \cup \rgc \cup \rspc$ is an expression that is mapped to |Omega| by the function $\omegavc$,
  which necessarily compares $\leqomegavc$ to any result produced by $\omegavc$ when applied to the right-hand side.
 \end{proof}

